WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.760
I want you to put yourself in a highly specific, but probably a very familiar scenario.

00:06.880 --> 00:08.440
Oh, I think we all know where this is going.

00:08.800 --> 00:09.100
Right.

00:09.520 --> 00:11.440
So, you are sitting on your couch.

00:11.980 --> 00:13.900
It's late, maybe 9 or 10 at night.

00:14.020 --> 00:14.320
Yeah.

00:15.040 --> 00:16.380
You're halfway through a movie.

00:16.900 --> 00:22.500
The living room is completely dark, and your phone buzzes on the coffee table.

00:22.700 --> 00:23.020
Uh-oh.

00:23.020 --> 00:24.160
You pick it up.

00:24.600 --> 00:29.720
The screen brightness totally hits your eyes, and you see a text message from a friend.

00:30.280 --> 00:31.560
Or, you know, maybe a partner.

00:31.900 --> 00:33.140
The stakes are getting higher.

00:33.340 --> 00:33.760
Exactly.

00:34.180 --> 00:39.520
And you had just asked them a fairly loaded question about your plans for the upcoming weekend.

00:39.800 --> 00:42.160
Something that required some actual coordination.

00:42.440 --> 00:42.780
Right.

00:42.960 --> 00:44.300
Maybe a little bit of compromise.

00:44.640 --> 00:48.520
And their response is just one single word, followed by a period.

00:48.780 --> 00:49.780
Oh, no.

00:50.440 --> 00:50.740
Fine.

00:50.740 --> 00:51.180
Fine.

00:51.320 --> 00:53.320
It is the ultimate digital trap.

00:53.660 --> 00:54.840
I mean, it really is.

00:54.880 --> 00:55.860
It's terrifying.

00:55.860 --> 01:02.180
You're suddenly holding this tiny, glowing rectangle, staring at four letters, and your

01:02.180 --> 01:05.080
brain is just shifting into absolute overdrive.

01:05.140 --> 01:06.360
And it has to, right.

01:06.440 --> 01:09.900
Because you have absolutely zero acoustic context.

01:10.100 --> 01:10.760
None at all.

01:10.800 --> 01:13.060
Is that an angry, jaw-clenched fine?

01:13.640 --> 01:13.840
Right.

01:13.920 --> 01:16.500
Like, I am furious, but I am agreeing.

01:16.780 --> 01:17.260
Exactly.

01:17.640 --> 01:21.440
Or is it a happy, easygoing, sure, whatever you want, that's fine.

01:21.440 --> 01:26.780
Or maybe it's just an exhausted fine, like, I just worked a 12-hour shift, and I cannot

01:26.780 --> 01:28.340
make a single decision right now.

01:28.600 --> 01:28.880
Fine.

01:29.400 --> 01:29.700
Yes.

01:30.320 --> 01:38.980
Or, worst of all, is it that dreaded, passive-aggressive fine that actually means the exact, literal

01:38.980 --> 01:40.420
opposite of fine?

01:40.660 --> 01:41.140
Oh, yeah.

01:41.220 --> 01:44.800
The one where you are about to walk into a complete minefield.

01:44.900 --> 01:47.440
Plain text just leaves you entirely in the dark.

01:47.440 --> 01:54.260
You're essentially playing detective with a crime scene that has been, um, completely

01:54.260 --> 01:55.480
scrubbed of fingerprints.

01:55.840 --> 01:57.240
That's a great way to put it.

01:57.300 --> 02:02.760
The actual evidence of the human emotion has been structurally removed from the medium

02:02.760 --> 02:03.260
itself.

02:03.420 --> 02:07.480
Which, you know, brings us to the core mission of today's deep dive.

02:07.720 --> 02:08.060
Yes.

02:08.240 --> 02:09.040
Let's get into it.

02:09.040 --> 02:17.060
We are unpacking a genuinely mind-bending, dense, and frankly, just revolutionary research

02:17.060 --> 02:17.800
paper today.

02:17.880 --> 02:19.160
It really is something else.

02:19.160 --> 02:22.140
It's by an independent researcher named Flyxion.

02:22.540 --> 02:29.960
And the paper is titled Hyperbionic Reading, A Visual Projection of Prosotic Parameter Space.

02:30.220 --> 02:31.040
Quite a mouthful.

02:31.340 --> 02:31.940
It is.

02:31.940 --> 02:38.020
But we are going to explore a very real, highly engineered argument here.

02:38.540 --> 02:45.620
The argument that the way human beings read and write is on the verge of a massive fundamental

02:45.620 --> 02:46.460
evolution.

02:46.880 --> 02:48.280
A total paradigm shift.

02:48.360 --> 02:55.680
We are talking about moving away from text as a flat, dead representation of a word and

02:55.680 --> 02:59.200
moving toward a higher dimensional visual medium.

02:59.200 --> 03:04.820
A medium where you can actually look at a word on a screen and physically see the music.

03:05.080 --> 03:05.360
Yes.

03:05.760 --> 03:11.640
See the hesitation, the rhythm, the emotional weight of the human voice that produced it.

03:11.880 --> 03:15.340
And, you know, the ambition of this paper is what makes it so compelling.

03:15.540 --> 03:16.240
Oh, absolutely.

03:16.500 --> 03:19.760
To pull this off, the author doesn't just look at typography.

03:20.520 --> 03:25.660
I mean, we're going to be digging into the underlying physics of acoustic waveforms.

03:25.880 --> 03:27.360
Advanced signal processing.

03:27.360 --> 03:27.780
Right.

03:27.780 --> 03:33.900
Human physiology, cognitive science, and even the structural mechanics of American sign language.

03:34.040 --> 03:38.640
It challenges the entire foundation of what we consider writing in the digital age.

03:38.860 --> 03:39.680
It really does.

03:39.920 --> 03:43.920
And if you are listening right now and thinking, okay, well, this sounds like a graphic design

03:43.920 --> 03:45.240
critique about a new font.

03:45.360 --> 03:46.160
Why should I care?

03:46.500 --> 03:46.700
Right.

03:46.760 --> 03:48.100
Like, why does this matter to me?

03:48.340 --> 03:48.820
Exactly.

03:49.300 --> 03:51.400
I want to set the stakes right now.

03:51.700 --> 03:54.300
This is not about making your emails look pretty.

03:54.460 --> 03:55.020
Not at all.

03:55.020 --> 04:01.460
This is about the subconscious biological energy you burn every single day trying to decode the

04:01.460 --> 04:02.580
tone of your coworkers.

04:02.940 --> 04:03.640
It's exhausting.

04:04.080 --> 04:04.500
It is.

04:04.700 --> 04:13.400
And it's also about a potentially foolproof method to expose AI deepfakes and biometric fraud.

04:13.540 --> 04:15.060
Which is huge right now.

04:15.060 --> 04:15.860
Massive.

04:15.860 --> 04:22.160
And it's about how the fundamental act of reading something you do for hours a day might completely

04:22.160 --> 04:24.420
transform in the next few years.

04:24.620 --> 04:25.940
So where do we start?

04:26.280 --> 04:28.720
Let's start with the foundational premise of the paper.

04:29.160 --> 04:34.420
It describes written language as a lossy projection of speech.

04:34.840 --> 04:35.160
Right.

04:35.400 --> 04:36.460
Lossy projection.

04:36.460 --> 04:39.340
Let's define what that actually means in this context.

04:39.720 --> 04:46.420
Well, lossy projection is a concept lifted directly from data compression and information

04:46.420 --> 04:47.080
theory.

04:47.240 --> 04:47.480
Okay.

04:47.580 --> 04:49.200
So like computer science stuff.

04:49.420 --> 04:49.900
Exactly.

04:50.440 --> 04:56.400
When a human being speaks, the voice is an incredibly rich, continuous, high-dimensional

04:56.400 --> 04:56.960
signal.

04:57.180 --> 04:58.320
There's a lot going on.

04:58.720 --> 04:59.520
So much.

04:59.520 --> 05:05.400
It has frequency, amplitude, microfluquations in timing, resonance.

05:05.920 --> 05:11.660
But when we transcribe that speech into standard written language.

05:11.940 --> 05:13.000
Like the English alphabet.

05:13.260 --> 05:13.420
Right.

05:13.480 --> 05:14.500
Like standard letters.

05:15.000 --> 05:17.540
We are performing a severe act of compression.

05:17.760 --> 05:19.200
We're squishing it down.

05:19.380 --> 05:25.360
The paper argues that standard text preserves the lexical structure.

05:25.820 --> 05:26.060
Yeah.

05:26.060 --> 05:28.200
It gives you the actual words and the grammar.

05:28.200 --> 05:31.320
But it completely discards the prosody.

05:31.760 --> 05:33.280
And prosody is the how, right?

05:33.480 --> 05:34.140
Yes, exactly.

05:34.180 --> 05:39.440
It's the pitch, the timing, the emotional weight, even the acoustic space of the room

05:39.440 --> 05:40.320
you're standing in.

05:40.380 --> 05:40.940
All of that.

05:41.380 --> 05:41.700
Gone.

05:42.120 --> 05:46.720
So the text preserves what you said, but violently strips away how you said it.

05:46.820 --> 05:49.540
That is what the paper calls the tragedy of the transcript.

05:49.780 --> 05:51.220
The tragedy of the transcript.

05:51.440 --> 05:52.060
I like that.

05:52.140 --> 05:53.300
And it's not an accident.

05:53.860 --> 05:57.200
It is a structural consequence of the technology we call the alphabet.

05:57.200 --> 05:59.360
Wait, the alphabet is a technology.

05:59.460 --> 06:00.180
Oh, absolutely.

06:01.020 --> 06:06.200
You are taking a continuous, unbroken wave of physical pressure.

06:06.520 --> 06:09.920
A wave that contains all of your emotional intent.

06:10.300 --> 06:16.360
And you are forcing it into a discrete, rigid sequence of categories.

06:16.680 --> 06:18.080
Those categories being letters.

06:18.260 --> 06:18.540
Okay.

06:18.760 --> 06:21.480
Let me try to visualize this dimensional loss for a second.

06:21.680 --> 06:22.240
Go for it.

06:22.240 --> 06:29.560
Think about taking a photograph with a high-end professional camera shooting in a raw format.

06:30.040 --> 06:31.340
Oh, I like this analogy.

06:31.560 --> 06:31.740
Right.

06:32.100 --> 06:34.580
That raw file is massive.

06:35.020 --> 06:43.120
It captures literal photon counts, incredible depth of field, millions of subtle color gradients,

06:43.320 --> 06:45.180
the exact lighting conditions.

06:45.400 --> 06:46.700
It's a huge amount of data.

06:46.700 --> 06:50.760
It is a high-dimensional, continuous representation of that moment.

06:50.960 --> 06:51.060
Yeah.

06:51.240 --> 06:56.820
But then you need to send that photo to a friend over a terrible, slow internet connection.

06:57.100 --> 06:58.240
So you have to compress it.

06:58.700 --> 06:59.140
Exactly.

06:59.380 --> 07:04.400
You turn it into a tiny, heavily pixelated, low-resolution JPEG.

07:04.520 --> 07:04.820
Right.

07:04.820 --> 07:08.900
Now, your friend looks at the JPEG, and they can still tell it's a picture of a dog.

07:09.000 --> 07:10.540
The lexical structure is there.

07:10.620 --> 07:10.980
Yes.

07:11.580 --> 07:17.640
But the nuanced lighting, the depth, the texture of the fur, the prosody is completely gone.

07:18.060 --> 07:23.340
And if we apply that analogy to human communication, the paper makes a fascinating point about cognitive

07:23.340 --> 07:23.820
load.

07:23.980 --> 07:24.220
Okay.

07:24.360 --> 07:25.080
Cognitive load.

07:25.160 --> 07:25.880
Break that down.

07:25.880 --> 07:32.280
If text is a highly compressed, terrible JPEG of human thought, your brain has to do an

07:32.280 --> 07:35.500
unbelievable amount of heavy lifting to make it useful.

07:35.700 --> 07:37.700
Because there are so many gaps to fill.

07:38.040 --> 07:38.600
Precisely.

07:39.000 --> 07:47.760
To survive this lossy text, your brain aggressively predicts and fills in the missing emotional

07:47.760 --> 07:50.620
data based on surrounding context.

07:50.620 --> 07:56.300
Wait, so when I read a really beautifully written novel, and I find myself actually crying

07:56.300 --> 08:00.400
at a line of dialogue, the emotion isn't actually in the text.

08:00.640 --> 08:01.520
Not directly.

08:01.960 --> 08:02.100
No.

08:02.180 --> 08:02.700
Cognitive load.

08:03.140 --> 08:09.640
The author provided enough contextual clues, descriptions of the setting, the character's

08:09.640 --> 08:12.000
past, the pacing of the sentences.

08:12.220 --> 08:12.520
Right.

08:12.720 --> 08:16.300
That your brain successfully hallucinated the correct prosody.

08:16.760 --> 08:17.560
Hallucinated it.

08:17.560 --> 08:20.520
You reconstructed the emotional weight internally.

08:21.520 --> 08:24.940
But that reconstruction is an active biological process.

08:25.040 --> 08:26.020
It takes effort.

08:26.360 --> 08:27.840
It requires cognitive effort.

08:28.000 --> 08:29.560
It literally burns calories.

08:29.760 --> 08:35.000
So when I am staring at the word fine on my phone, the reason I feel stressed isn't

08:35.000 --> 08:36.940
just because I'm worried about my friend being mad.

08:37.140 --> 08:44.140
It's because my brain is actively spinning its wheels, burning biological energy, trying

08:44.140 --> 08:48.580
to render an emotional reality that the text actively hid from me.

08:48.580 --> 08:53.600
Well, you are experiencing the friction of a lossy projection.

08:53.740 --> 08:54.540
The friction.

08:55.480 --> 09:01.800
And this friction has recently led to various attempts to kind of fix reading.

09:02.040 --> 09:02.620
Fix reading?

09:02.700 --> 09:03.340
Like how?

09:03.960 --> 09:10.080
Well, the paper points to a very popular recent trend to illustrate where we might be going

09:10.080 --> 09:10.560
wrong.

09:10.740 --> 09:11.180
Oh, okay.

09:11.180 --> 09:18.600
It contrasts the proposed hyperbionic reading with something that currently exists called

09:18.600 --> 09:19.660
bionic reading.

09:19.800 --> 09:22.460
Oh, I have actually used bionic reading.

09:22.620 --> 09:22.980
You have?

09:23.060 --> 09:23.240
Yeah.

09:23.320 --> 09:25.520
It's a browser extension you can download.

09:25.740 --> 09:30.340
It was developed by a Swiss designer, Renato Casut, I think.

09:30.500 --> 09:30.960
That's right.

09:30.960 --> 09:37.060
The way it works is it bowls the initial letters of words to create artificial fixation points.

09:37.240 --> 09:37.640
Exactly.

09:37.860 --> 09:42.940
So if you have the word fascinating, the FAS is thick and bold, and the rest of the word

09:42.940 --> 09:44.140
is normal weight.

09:44.320 --> 09:45.980
And how did it feel to use it?

09:46.220 --> 09:50.300
I will admit, it feels a little weird the first time you look at a page formatted this

09:50.300 --> 09:50.580
way.

09:50.660 --> 09:51.740
It looks a bit jarring.

09:52.020 --> 09:52.580
It does.

09:52.580 --> 09:57.820
But it genuinely feels like my eyes are just gliding over the text at twice the speed.

09:58.200 --> 09:58.680
And it works.

09:58.680 --> 10:02.040
The paper does not dispute its efficacy at all.

10:02.400 --> 10:02.640
Okay.

10:02.840 --> 10:03.900
So it's a real thing.

10:04.400 --> 10:07.800
Bionic reading is grounded in established reading science.

10:08.700 --> 10:14.160
When you are a fluent reader, you do not decode words serially, character by character.

10:14.420 --> 10:14.700
Right.

10:14.800 --> 10:16.820
I'm not sounding out C-A-E-T anymore.

10:16.920 --> 10:17.420
Exactly.

10:18.320 --> 10:21.480
Reading is a predictive, pattern-matching process.

10:21.480 --> 10:29.540
Your brain scans for the prefix Q, what linguists call an n-gram, the first few letters.

10:29.820 --> 10:30.120
Yeah.

10:30.320 --> 10:35.200
And based on your vocabulary, it just predicts the rest of the word.

10:35.260 --> 10:36.480
It just auto-fills it.

10:36.600 --> 10:42.340
By bolding those initial letters, bionic reading acts like a high contrast throttle for your brain's

10:42.340 --> 10:43.760
internal prediction engine.

10:43.760 --> 10:45.200
That makes total sense.

10:45.500 --> 10:50.560
It is highly documented to help with reading speed, particularly for individuals with ADHD

10:50.560 --> 10:54.720
or dyslexia, because it reduces the visual search time.

10:55.300 --> 10:55.560
Okay.

10:55.720 --> 11:00.420
But if it works and it reduces visual search time, what is the problem?

11:00.960 --> 11:01.320
Well...

11:01.320 --> 11:06.000
Why does this paper argue we need to shift to hyperbionic reading?

11:06.180 --> 11:11.820
Because bionic reading fundamentally equates meaning with lexical recognition speed.

11:12.180 --> 11:13.040
Wait, say that again?

11:13.620 --> 11:18.160
It operates on the assumption that all the vital information is already present in the text,

11:18.440 --> 11:21.640
and the only problem is that you aren't decoding it fast enough.

11:21.780 --> 11:22.180
Ah.

11:22.760 --> 11:25.460
It's just trying to make the JPEG load faster.

11:25.860 --> 11:26.420
Precisely.

11:26.820 --> 11:29.800
It is optimizing the retrieval of the JPEG.

11:29.980 --> 11:30.380
Wow.

11:30.380 --> 11:34.300
Hyperbionic reading operates on the completely opposite assumption.

11:34.540 --> 11:35.040
Which is?

11:35.180 --> 11:36.760
That the vital information is missing.

11:37.160 --> 11:42.800
It was structurally removed during the transcription process, and speeding up your reading won't

11:42.800 --> 11:43.540
bring it back.

11:43.660 --> 11:48.760
So reading a bad text message faster doesn't help me figure out if my friend is mad.

11:48.880 --> 11:49.340
Exactly.

11:49.620 --> 11:53.760
The missing prosody must be projected back into the visual field.

11:53.940 --> 11:54.580
Okay, look.

11:54.800 --> 11:56.780
I am 35 years old.

11:57.120 --> 11:59.060
I read English perfectly well.

11:59.160 --> 11:59.380
Right.

11:59.380 --> 12:07.520
If I am trying to get through a dense 10-page legal contract, or even just a long news article,

12:07.640 --> 12:08.760
I want to speed read.

12:08.920 --> 12:09.220
Sure.

12:09.480 --> 12:15.500
The idea of adding more visual information to the page, even if it represents the emotion

12:15.500 --> 12:20.960
of the writer, sounds like it would just create massive visual clutter.

12:20.960 --> 12:22.480
It's a valid concern.

12:22.480 --> 12:26.560
Doesn't this completely destroy my ability to skim text efficiently?

12:27.100 --> 12:29.300
Well, if your only goal is...

12:29.300 --> 12:32.180
But what happens if you are a new language learner?

12:32.940 --> 12:39.180
Or, more commonly, what happens when you are reading a text message from a friend where the

12:39.180 --> 12:41.480
emotional register is highly ambiguous?

12:41.480 --> 12:43.440
The fine scenario.

12:43.440 --> 12:43.880
Exactly.

12:43.880 --> 12:48.660
In those moments, your internal model isn't enough.

12:49.440 --> 12:51.400
Because the text is too sparse.

12:51.400 --> 12:54.580
So, I guess wrong, and I start a fight.

12:54.700 --> 12:54.920
Right.

12:55.920 --> 12:58.840
Hyperbionic text is not designed to make you read faster.

12:59.360 --> 13:04.700
It is designed to give your brain the exact tonal structure of the utterance so that you

13:04.700 --> 13:05.880
do not have to guess.

13:06.100 --> 13:07.660
It does the heavy lifting for me.

13:07.660 --> 13:13.860
If the visual text explicitly encodes the geometry of the emotion, you are spared the

13:13.860 --> 13:15.560
cognitive load of hallucination.

13:15.560 --> 13:19.680
The text hands the reality directly to you.

13:19.940 --> 13:20.380
Okay.

13:20.540 --> 13:25.920
So, the theoretical goal is to hand the reader the exact emotional reality of the speaker?

13:26.240 --> 13:26.560
Yes.

13:26.760 --> 13:28.260
But how do you actually do that?

13:28.380 --> 13:33.580
Like, how do you capture the invisible ghost of a human voice, the hesitation, the breath,

13:33.800 --> 13:36.980
and mathematically trap it so it can be put on a screen?

13:37.200 --> 13:38.580
That is the million dollar question.

13:38.940 --> 13:41.540
This leads us to the mechanics of the system, right?

13:42.040 --> 13:45.900
Specifically, a tool the paper introduces called the marine processor.

13:46.480 --> 13:47.980
Yes, the marine processor.

13:48.260 --> 13:51.420
It is the acoustic engine of this entire concept.

13:51.620 --> 13:51.880
Okay.

13:52.040 --> 13:52.800
Walk me through it.

13:53.260 --> 13:59.040
In the paper's mathematical notation, it is represented by the measurement operator, a

13:59.040 --> 13:59.660
capital M.

13:59.740 --> 14:00.380
Capital M.

14:00.500 --> 14:00.920
Got it.

14:00.920 --> 14:09.160
It's job is to take a raw acoustic waveform, an audio recording of someone speaking, and

14:09.160 --> 14:12.740
extract a very specific eight-dimensional vector.

14:12.740 --> 14:16.400
I need an explanation of this eight-dimensional vector.

14:16.980 --> 14:23.460
If we are taking a highly complex audio recording and blowing it down to just eight numbers, what

14:23.460 --> 14:25.460
exactly are those eight numbers measuring?

14:25.460 --> 14:31.320
Well, the marine processor is not trying to record the audio perfectly, like an MP3 would.

14:31.400 --> 14:31.740
Okay.

14:32.360 --> 14:36.700
It is isolating specific physical invariants of the speech.

14:36.840 --> 14:37.460
Physical invariants.

14:38.080 --> 14:39.380
Things that don't change.

14:39.780 --> 14:41.940
Let's break down a few of the most critical ones.

14:42.360 --> 14:44.720
First, it measures period jitter.

14:45.040 --> 14:46.020
Period jitter.

14:46.300 --> 14:47.620
This is in the time domain.

14:48.120 --> 14:54.600
It measures how much the timing of the vocal pitch deviates from absolute metronomic perfection.

14:54.600 --> 14:58.140
From one vibration of your vocal cords to the neck.

14:58.240 --> 15:01.400
Wait, so my vocal cords don't vibrate perfectly evenly?

15:02.020 --> 15:02.540
Not at all.

15:02.620 --> 15:03.580
They're organic tissue.

15:04.400 --> 15:07.900
Next is amplitude jitter, which is in the energy domain.

15:08.040 --> 15:08.260
Okay.

15:08.460 --> 15:11.440
It measures the micro fluctuations in the volume of the voice.

15:11.660 --> 15:16.880
So period jitter is when my voice wavers in pitch, and amplitude jitter is when my voice

15:16.880 --> 15:18.020
wavers in loudness.

15:18.180 --> 15:19.220
Essentially, yes.

15:19.780 --> 15:22.000
It also measures harmonic coherence.

15:23.540 --> 15:24.580
Harmonic coherence.

15:24.600 --> 15:26.040
That sounds musical.

15:26.280 --> 15:26.780
It is.

15:27.200 --> 15:32.260
When your vocal cords vibrate, they create a fundamental frequency, but they also create

15:32.260 --> 15:34.420
overtones, or harmonics.

15:34.580 --> 15:36.280
Like when you pluck a guitar string.

15:36.460 --> 15:37.060
Exactly.

15:37.700 --> 15:44.140
Harmonic coherence measures the degree of periodic regularity in that complex sound.

15:44.300 --> 15:45.360
Meaning what, practically?

15:45.360 --> 15:52.920
If you are speaking with a clear, resonant, confident voice, your harmonic coherence is very high.

15:53.180 --> 15:53.500
Okay.

15:53.720 --> 16:00.740
But if your voice is raspy, breathy, or strained, the harmonic coherence drops significantly.

16:00.740 --> 16:02.240
Ah, okay.

16:02.600 --> 16:03.200
I get that.

16:03.340 --> 16:09.480
The processor also tracks a salience index, peak density, means squared amplitude, and others.

16:10.300 --> 16:15.460
Eight distinct metrics that together map the architectural structure of how you spoke.

16:15.460 --> 16:19.460
But the way it extracts these measurements is what I find really counterintuitive.

16:20.340 --> 16:20.660
Awesome.

16:21.060 --> 16:27.320
Normally, if I open up audio recording software on my computer, it uses uniform sampling.

16:27.680 --> 16:27.960
Right.

16:27.960 --> 16:35.660
It takes a measurement of the sound wave every single millisecond, maybe 44,000 times a second,

16:35.880 --> 16:39.380
capturing every tiny dip and rise in the wave.

16:39.500 --> 16:40.600
Standard digital audio.

16:40.680 --> 16:40.960
Right.

16:41.420 --> 16:45.680
But the marine processor uses something called event-based sampling.

16:46.720 --> 16:49.040
Why wouldn't we want all the data?

16:49.400 --> 16:56.460
Because a vast amount of that data in uniform sampling is completely irrelevant to the

16:56.460 --> 16:58.060
prasonic intent of the speaker.

16:58.380 --> 16:58.940
Irrelevant.

16:59.340 --> 16:59.680
How?

17:00.020 --> 17:00.820
Think of it this way.

17:01.300 --> 17:06.920
Uniform sampling treats every microsecond of the audio file with equal importance,

17:07.360 --> 17:11.260
including the dead space and the random acoustic noise of the room.

17:11.260 --> 17:15.420
So it's recording the hum of my refrigerator with the same fidelity as my voice.

17:15.560 --> 17:16.080
Exactly.

17:16.740 --> 17:21.820
The marine processor's event-based sampling only grabs the local maxima of the signal.

17:21.980 --> 17:22.860
Local maxima?

17:23.000 --> 17:23.540
The peaks.

17:23.540 --> 17:28.920
It scans the audio and only takes a measurement when the energy peaks above a certain dynamic

17:28.920 --> 17:29.560
threshold.

17:29.720 --> 17:30.040
Oh.

17:30.520 --> 17:32.080
It's like looking up at the night sky.

17:32.680 --> 17:32.960
Okay.

17:33.160 --> 17:34.480
I like where you're going with this.

17:34.740 --> 17:40.660
If you want to draw a constellation, you don't take a measuring tape and measure every

17:40.660 --> 17:45.180
single inch of the vast, black, empty space between the stars.

17:45.400 --> 17:46.060
No, you don't.

17:46.060 --> 17:52.060
You only identify the brightest stars, the local maxima, and you track the geometric relationship

17:52.060 --> 17:52.780
between them.

17:53.200 --> 17:54.840
The empty space doesn't matter.

17:55.100 --> 17:57.260
The bright points dictate the shape.

17:57.880 --> 18:00.320
That is a brilliant analogy, yes.

18:01.020 --> 18:07.480
And to track the shape of the pitch specifically across those stars, the system uses a mathematical

18:07.480 --> 18:11.960
technique called an exponential moving average, or EMA.

18:12.480 --> 18:14.500
Let's unpack the math behind the EMA.

18:14.940 --> 18:20.340
Why is it so crucial for human speech compared to just calculating a normal average?

18:20.520 --> 18:25.880
Well, if you calculate a simple moving average, you take the last, say, 50 measurements of pitch,

18:26.260 --> 18:27.980
add them up, and divide by 50.

18:28.060 --> 18:28.260
Right.

18:28.320 --> 18:28.940
Standard math.

18:28.940 --> 18:34.940
Every data point from the past carries the exact same weight as the data point from a millisecond

18:34.940 --> 18:35.200
ago.

18:35.300 --> 18:35.500
Okay.

18:35.580 --> 18:36.420
Why is that bad?

18:36.820 --> 18:42.220
The problem with this in speech processing is that human voices naturally drift.

18:42.700 --> 18:45.140
Think about how you speak a long sentence.

18:46.080 --> 18:51.520
As you run out of breath toward the end of the sentence, your fundamental pitch naturally

18:51.520 --> 18:51.980
lowers.

18:52.620 --> 18:54.860
This is called vocal declination.

18:55.060 --> 18:55.300
Right.

18:55.420 --> 18:58.500
My voice drops because my lungs are literally emptying out.

18:58.500 --> 18:59.180
Exactly.

18:59.700 --> 19:08.180
If a classical audio processing system assumes a stationary, perfect baseline pitch, it will

19:08.180 --> 19:12.660
look at your dropping voice at the end of the sentence and flag it as an error.

19:12.820 --> 19:14.540
It thinks I'm making a mistake.

19:14.900 --> 19:18.340
It will register it as massive jitter or instability.

19:19.220 --> 19:23.540
But an exponential moving average calculates the baseline differently.

19:23.800 --> 19:24.440
How so?

19:24.440 --> 19:30.740
It assigns exponentially more mathematical weight to the most recent data points and less weight

19:30.740 --> 19:31.700
to the older ones.

19:31.800 --> 19:32.860
So it has a short memory.

19:33.060 --> 19:33.800
It adapts.

19:33.940 --> 19:34.460
Precisely.

19:35.000 --> 19:39.640
The EMA creates a locally adaptive reference line that slides along with your voice.

19:39.760 --> 19:40.940
It updates in real time.

19:40.940 --> 19:47.640
It mathematically recognizes that your gradual lowering of pitch is a natural physiological

19:47.640 --> 19:50.620
prosodic intent, not a degradation of the signal.

19:50.620 --> 19:56.320
It tracks the contour of your intent rather than punishing you for not sounding like a robot

19:56.320 --> 19:57.480
or a synthesizer.

19:57.860 --> 20:00.700
Okay, but I have a major conceptual hurdle here.

20:00.840 --> 20:01.300
Let's hear it.

20:01.300 --> 20:07.680
You just said that text is a terrible lossy JPEG because it compresses the complex reality

20:07.680 --> 20:10.540
of human speech into a few discrete letters.

20:10.900 --> 20:11.620
I did see that.

20:11.620 --> 20:20.040
But now we are taking a rich audio recording, ignoring most of the data through event-based

20:20.040 --> 20:25.320
sampling, and boiling the remainder down to just eight numbers.

20:25.800 --> 20:26.080
Right.

20:26.340 --> 20:29.580
Aren't we just creating a different kind of lossy projection?

20:29.720 --> 20:32.460
Haven't we just built a slightly fancier JPEG?

20:32.460 --> 20:37.960
From a pure data volume perspective, yes, information is absolutely being discarded.

20:38.120 --> 20:38.340
Ah.

20:39.300 --> 20:46.100
But, and this is key, the paper mounts a rigorous defense of what is being discarded.

20:46.240 --> 20:46.680
Oh, okay.

20:46.780 --> 20:51.760
The measurement operator is not a compressed representation in the traditional information

20:51.760 --> 20:52.880
theoretic sense.

20:53.000 --> 20:53.640
What does that mean?

20:53.940 --> 20:59.240
It discards the microscopic within utterance acoustic variations that do not carry structural

20:59.240 --> 21:00.520
or emotional meaning.

21:00.520 --> 21:01.760
It throws out the trash.

21:01.760 --> 21:02.400
Exactly.

21:02.600 --> 21:06.840
It filters out the noise of the specific microphone or the hum of the air conditioner.

21:07.600 --> 21:13.420
What survives this filtering process, those eight numbers, are the prosodic invariants.

21:13.820 --> 21:19.520
Prosodic invariants, meaning the core unchangeable truth of the emotion.

21:19.820 --> 21:20.100
Yes.

21:20.800 --> 21:26.820
The paper explicitly states that the system does not preserve waveforms.

21:27.080 --> 21:28.980
It preserves equivalence classes.

21:29.220 --> 21:30.120
Equivalence classes.

21:30.120 --> 21:35.780
It captures the physical geometry that your brain actually uses to determine if a speaker

21:35.780 --> 21:39.880
is being sincere or sarcastic or hesitant.

21:40.380 --> 21:40.740
Wow.

21:40.880 --> 21:46.140
It drops the data you don't need and isolates the exact data you used to feel.

21:46.260 --> 21:47.840
So we have our eight-dimensional vector.

21:47.840 --> 21:54.500
We have successfully captured the mathematical geometry of sarcasm or exhaustion or joy.

21:54.500 --> 21:55.420
We have the numbers.

21:55.420 --> 21:56.960
Now comes the translation.

21:57.380 --> 22:01.980
How do those eight invisible numbers actually become visible text on a screen?

22:02.580 --> 22:07.960
This involves the typographic rendering operator, which the paper denotes with a capital R.

22:08.080 --> 22:14.240
Capital R. So M is for the marine processor that measures and R is for the operator that renders.

22:14.240 --> 22:14.900
I got it.

22:15.580 --> 22:19.700
This is where the highly theoretical math becomes a visual user interface.

22:19.780 --> 22:20.640
I love this part.

22:20.900 --> 22:26.800
The paper provides a matrix, table one, that acts as a direct translation protocol.

22:26.800 --> 22:35.980
It maps the invisible acoustic parameters extracted by the marine processor directly to the visual properties of standard typography.

22:35.980 --> 22:42.540
I really want to walk through this translation matrix carefully because this is where you, listening right now,

22:42.620 --> 22:48.060
can really start to visualize what your text message app is going to look like in five years.

22:48.120 --> 22:49.060
It's going to be wild.

22:49.280 --> 22:52.240
Let's start with the basics, energy and pitch.

22:52.540 --> 22:52.820
Okay.

22:53.400 --> 23:01.280
The acoustic energy of the voice, the raw amplitude or loudness, maps to the font size and the font weight.

23:01.280 --> 23:08.000
So a louder, more forceful utterance renders as physically larger, bolder type.

23:08.280 --> 23:08.760
Exactly.

23:09.100 --> 23:10.560
That one feels super intuitive.

23:10.760 --> 23:15.320
I mean, we already kind of simulate that when we type in all CKS to yell at someone on the internet.

23:15.480 --> 23:16.820
Right. It's a natural instinct.

23:16.940 --> 23:17.880
But what about pitch?

23:18.060 --> 23:22.620
The fundamental pitch of the voice maps to vertical baseline displacement.

23:22.760 --> 23:25.740
Wait, so the letters literally move up and down on the screen?

23:25.980 --> 23:26.280
Yes.

23:26.280 --> 23:34.480
If a speaker's pitch rises, say, at the end of a question, the letters physically move upward on the page,

23:35.140 --> 23:37.920
deviating above the standard horizontal line.

23:38.280 --> 23:39.000
Oh, wow.

23:39.000 --> 23:47.160
And as the pitch drops, perhaps when a speaker is muttering or sighing, the letters sink below the baseline.

23:47.160 --> 23:56.540
So a sentence spoken with a highly varied, melodic voice would look like a literal rollercoaster of text across the screen.

23:56.880 --> 23:58.820
Precisely. You could see the melody.

23:59.140 --> 24:00.620
What about the speed of the speaker?

24:01.020 --> 24:07.120
Duration, the temporal extension of the speech maps to letter spacing or tracking.

24:07.120 --> 24:08.480
Okay, so spacing.

24:08.960 --> 24:17.560
If a speaker draws out a word, saying it very slowly, the typographic rendering spaces, the letters wider apart.

24:17.860 --> 24:18.420
Makes sense.

24:18.500 --> 24:23.600
But if they speak in a rapid clipped burst, the letters are condensed tightly together.

24:23.800 --> 24:29.140
Okay, those first three, boldness, vertical shifting, and spacing I can wrap my head around.

24:29.360 --> 24:30.520
That's easy enough to picture.

24:30.720 --> 24:31.540
It gets weirder.

24:31.680 --> 24:35.420
Yeah, because the paper gets into parameters that are much harder to visualize.

24:35.420 --> 24:37.680
How does it render jitter?

24:38.380 --> 24:41.080
This is where the rendering becomes truly dynamic.

24:41.840 --> 24:47.540
Jitter, as we discussed, is the micro fluctuation, the physical tremor or vibrato in the voice.

24:47.800 --> 24:47.900
Right.

24:48.200 --> 24:52.440
The rendering operator maps jitter to the micro rotation of the glyphs.

24:52.660 --> 24:53.580
Micro rotation.

24:53.760 --> 24:59.720
The individual letters themselves are slightly tilted or rotated off their central axis.

24:59.720 --> 25:09.880
So if someone is terrified and their voice is shaking, the letters on the screen are literally tilting back and forth, vibrating on their axis.

25:10.420 --> 25:11.880
Visually, yes.

25:12.500 --> 25:18.960
You perceive the physical instability of the speaker's vocal cords as a visual instability of the font.

25:19.100 --> 25:20.380
That is crazy.

25:20.500 --> 25:22.480
And this is paired with the salience index.

25:22.580 --> 25:24.420
Remind me what salience is.

25:24.420 --> 25:31.580
Salience, how clear, resonant, and stable the acoustic signal is, maps to the opacity of the ink.

25:31.780 --> 25:32.420
Opacity.

25:32.700 --> 25:34.620
Like how see-through the letters are.

25:34.840 --> 25:35.240
Yes.

25:36.200 --> 25:41.380
A highly salient, confident voice is rendered in full, solid black.

25:41.880 --> 25:47.240
A weak, breathy, trailing voice becomes transparent and ghost-like.

25:47.380 --> 25:47.880
Oh, man.

25:48.280 --> 25:53.200
Combine those two and imagine getting a text message from someone who is whispering in fear.

25:53.200 --> 25:54.080
Picture it.

25:54.700 --> 25:57.500
The text would be physically small because the energy is low.

25:57.720 --> 26:02.000
The letters would be micro-rotating, tilting crazily because of the high jitter.

26:02.400 --> 26:06.480
And the ink itself would be faded and translucent because of the low salience.

26:06.540 --> 26:06.880
Yes.

26:06.960 --> 26:08.500
You wouldn't just read the words.

26:08.840 --> 26:12.240
You would be staring at the visual embodiment of sheer panic.

26:12.700 --> 26:14.760
It is a direct Senthry translation.

26:15.600 --> 26:17.080
You feel it in your eyes.

26:17.080 --> 26:23.160
And the paper goes even further, addressing how to render higher-dimensional acoustic features,

26:23.700 --> 26:26.380
like environmental delay and reverberation.

26:26.540 --> 26:26.940
Yes.

26:27.140 --> 26:29.280
The environmental rendering is wild.

26:29.680 --> 26:32.600
How does the text show that a voice is echoing?

26:32.640 --> 26:34.080
Like I'm shouting in a canyon.

26:34.080 --> 26:39.680
Think about what an echo or a delay actually is in acoustics.

26:40.020 --> 26:47.120
It is the exact same audio signal arriving at the listener's ear a moment later, usually at a reduced amplitude.

26:47.400 --> 26:47.680
Right.

26:47.680 --> 26:51.660
The typographic translation of this is a spatial duplication.

26:51.820 --> 26:52.940
Spatial duplication.

26:53.000 --> 27:04.520
The system literally copies the text, but the copy is offset horizontally and vertically behind the primary text, and its opacity is drastically reduced.

27:04.680 --> 27:05.800
It looks like a shadow.

27:06.260 --> 27:09.420
It looks like a spatial ghost of the word trailing behind the main glyph.

27:09.500 --> 27:11.240
What about reverberation?

27:11.660 --> 27:13.060
Reverb is slightly different.

27:13.060 --> 27:20.000
Like if I am listening to an audio recording of Martin Luther King Jr. delivering the I Have a Dream speech.

27:20.140 --> 27:21.160
Okay, great example.

27:21.420 --> 27:29.580
His voice is bouncing off the stone of the Lincoln Memorial and echoing across the massive open space of the National Mall.

27:30.280 --> 27:36.160
That acoustic reverb is a huge part of the emotional power of that speech.

27:36.320 --> 27:36.760
Absolutely.

27:37.260 --> 27:38.960
How does that translate to a page?

27:38.960 --> 27:46.980
Well, reverberation is acoustic energy persisting and smearing across time as it bounces around a physical space.

27:47.060 --> 27:47.380
Right.

27:47.520 --> 27:48.880
It's not a distinct echo.

27:49.040 --> 27:49.800
It's a smear.

27:50.240 --> 27:50.680
Exactly.

27:51.080 --> 27:56.140
The paper renders this visually as a convolutional halo.

27:56.420 --> 27:56.960
The halo.

27:57.160 --> 28:01.980
The text generates a blur or a shadow that spreads out from the center of the letters.

28:01.980 --> 28:11.400
If a voice is recorded in a tight carpeted closet, there's almost no reverb, so the letters have hard, crisp edges.

28:11.620 --> 28:13.140
Because the sound is deadened.

28:13.260 --> 28:13.700
Right.

28:14.220 --> 28:24.920
But if you read the transcript of Dr. King's speech rendered through the hyperbionic system, you would see massive, blurry, spreading halos radiating off the words.

28:25.060 --> 28:25.520
Wow.

28:25.820 --> 28:31.140
You would look at the page and visibly perceive the physical scale of the National Mall.

28:31.140 --> 28:32.620
Okay, stop right there.

28:32.900 --> 28:35.360
I have to push back on this, and I want to push back hard.

28:35.520 --> 28:36.160
Bring it on.

28:36.380 --> 28:38.880
I am picturing this page in my head right now.

28:39.200 --> 28:44.980
I am trying to read a news article, and the text is shifting up and down like a roller coaster.

28:45.580 --> 28:48.680
The letters are tilting and vibrating on their axes.

28:49.240 --> 28:51.600
Words are fading in and out of transparency.

28:52.600 --> 28:58.460
And massive, blurry halos and ghostly echoes are spreading all over my screen.

28:58.680 --> 28:59.520
Sounds intense.

28:59.520 --> 29:02.960
Honestly, it sounds like an absolute visual nightmare.

29:03.900 --> 29:08.600
I feel like trying to read this for more than 30 seconds would induce acute motion sickness.

29:09.100 --> 29:10.080
It sounds chaotic.

29:10.300 --> 29:16.240
Does the author of this paper completely ignore the fact that reading requires a stable visual field?

29:16.680 --> 29:22.120
It is the most obvious vulnerability of the concept, and the author anticipates it perfectly.

29:22.300 --> 29:23.100
They do.

29:23.100 --> 29:28.540
The paper introduces a highly strict mathematical safeguard called admissibility constraints.

29:29.540 --> 29:30.540
Admissibility constraints.

29:31.200 --> 29:37.580
The entire hyperbionic rendering system operates under a fundamental inviolable mandate.

29:37.880 --> 29:38.120
Yeah.

29:38.660 --> 29:40.540
It cannot violate baseline legibility.

29:40.540 --> 29:49.220
But how does a piece of software objectively define what is legally readable and what is a nauseating blur?

29:49.220 --> 29:53.760
It is managed through what the paper calls a constraint energy equation.

29:53.820 --> 29:57.880
The software doesn't just apply the visual transformations blindly.

29:57.880 --> 30:04.900
It constantly calculates the deviation of the typography from standard legibility metrics.

30:04.900 --> 30:07.440
So it's checking itself in real time.

30:07.940 --> 30:08.340
Exactly.

30:08.340 --> 30:20.220
For example, when applying a convolutional halo for reverb, the system continually calculates the pixel density and the contrast ratio of the blurred text against the background.

30:20.440 --> 30:20.920
Right.

30:21.080 --> 30:33.960
If the math indicates that the contrast ratio is dropping below the minimum threshold required for the human eye to easily distinguish the letter E from the letter C, the software hits a hard ceiling.

30:34.140 --> 30:35.160
It stops blurring.

30:35.320 --> 30:37.540
It artificially caps the halo effect.

30:37.540 --> 30:39.520
So it's a dynamic safety break.

30:40.000 --> 30:41.480
That's a perfect way to put it.

30:41.480 --> 30:50.480
The rendering is allowed to flex and bend to show emotion, but the math violently snaps it back if it crosses the line to illegibility.

30:50.960 --> 30:51.240
Yes.

30:52.120 --> 30:55.540
The text must remain within what is termed a stable manifold.

30:55.940 --> 30:57.080
Stable manifold.

30:57.600 --> 31:04.580
And to explain why this is physiologically necessary, the paper draws a brilliant parallel to audio engineering,

31:04.580 --> 31:08.520
specifically a phenomenon called spectral fracturing.

31:08.520 --> 31:10.580
What is spectral fracturing?

31:10.580 --> 31:20.960
Have you ever listened to an audio file that was heavily compressed, like a really low bitrate MP3 from the early 2000s, or a bad cell phone connection?

31:21.100 --> 31:22.040
Oh, yeah.

31:22.140 --> 31:25.540
It gets that weird metallic underwater ringing sound.

31:25.540 --> 31:26.280
Exactly.

31:26.920 --> 31:30.140
That metallic ringing is spectral fracturing.

31:30.860 --> 31:34.800
It is caused by quantization errors in the frequency domain.

31:34.980 --> 31:35.380
Okay.

31:35.800 --> 31:46.220
Now, even if your conscious mind is focused on the song or the conversation, your deeply evolved auditory system registers those unnatural metallic artifacts.

31:46.340 --> 31:47.820
Because it sounds wrong.

31:48.120 --> 31:48.400
Right.

31:48.400 --> 31:54.680
Processing that garbage data imposes a massive subconscious cognitive load on your brain.

31:54.860 --> 31:55.480
It's tiring.

31:55.720 --> 32:06.260
It actually induces fatigue, and it blunts your ability to feel the emotional impact of the music, because your brain is working so hard just to assemble the broken pieces.

32:06.460 --> 32:07.300
Oh, wow.

32:07.440 --> 32:16.440
So if the typography is too crazy, if it fractures the visual spectrum, my brain will get exhausted just trying to recognize the letters, and I won't feel the emotion anyway.

32:16.640 --> 32:17.160
Precisely.

32:17.160 --> 32:23.480
Bad typography does to the visual cortex exactly what a bad MP3 does to the auditory cortex.

32:23.540 --> 32:24.740
That makes so much sense.

32:25.280 --> 32:35.980
If the letters rotate too violently or blur too heavily, the cognitive load of decoding the word supersedes the benefit of the prosodic information.

32:36.180 --> 32:37.840
It defeats the whole purpose.

32:38.300 --> 32:43.540
Therefore, the admissibility constraints ensure that the visual shift is subtle.

32:44.120 --> 32:46.500
It is not a chaotic circus on the page.

32:46.500 --> 32:46.840
Right.

32:46.840 --> 32:56.820
It is a highly controlled, deeply intentional, mathematically bounded shift that preserves the emotion without ever triggering visual fatigue.

32:56.960 --> 32:58.120
That makes a lot more sense.

32:58.220 --> 33:01.160
It's about subtle modulation, not destroying the font.

33:01.280 --> 33:01.680
Exactly.

33:01.680 --> 33:07.620
Okay, so we have discussed how a single acoustic peak is measured and rendered.

33:07.900 --> 33:08.860
A single snapshot.

33:09.220 --> 33:09.420
Right.

33:09.800 --> 33:12.460
But a spoken word isn't a single peak.

33:13.220 --> 33:14.300
It takes time.

33:14.880 --> 33:18.500
A word like fascinating takes a half second or more to say.

33:19.140 --> 33:22.680
The pitch and the volume are evolving the entire time.

33:22.800 --> 33:24.380
Yes, it's a continuous event.

33:24.380 --> 33:32.380
How does this system stitch these individual millisecond snapshots together into a cohesive, recognizable word?

33:32.720 --> 33:38.560
This requires moving from the static measurements we've discussed into the temporal domain.

33:38.560 --> 33:39.900
The element of time.

33:39.900 --> 33:43.420
The paper states that words are not static points.

33:43.980 --> 33:45.540
They are continuous paths.

33:46.440 --> 33:52.740
It conceptualizes a spoken utterance as a trajectory through a modal lattice.

33:52.740 --> 33:55.100
A trajectory through a modal lattice.

33:55.500 --> 33:59.660
Okay, I'm going to use you to break that down for me like I'm five years old, but keep the math intact.

33:59.780 --> 34:01.040
Okay, let's visualize this.

34:01.760 --> 34:07.040
Imagine a massive, invisible, multidimensional scaffolding.

34:07.120 --> 34:07.740
Okay, scaffolding?

34:08.460 --> 34:10.000
This is the modal lattice.

34:10.000 --> 34:18.520
It represents every possible combination of pitch, volume, jitter, and salience that a human voice could produce.

34:18.800 --> 34:21.920
So it's the space of all possible sounds.

34:22.100 --> 34:22.420
Yes.

34:23.200 --> 34:29.180
When you speak a word, your voice acts like a glowing dot moving through that scaffolding.

34:29.260 --> 34:29.600
Okay.

34:29.760 --> 34:35.120
The specific path that dot takes over the course of half a second is the trajectory of the word.

34:35.120 --> 34:39.980
So my voice is carving a specific, measurable path through this acoustic space.

34:40.100 --> 34:40.340
Yes.

34:40.900 --> 34:45.440
And the system stores these paths as what the author calls word basins.

34:45.600 --> 34:46.400
Word basins.

34:46.500 --> 34:47.380
Like a river basin.

34:47.760 --> 34:52.840
Think of a word basin as a deep groove or a trench in the modal lattice.

34:53.940 --> 35:03.700
Every time you say the word hello, your voice traces a slightly different path, but it generally follows the same overall geometric shape.

35:03.700 --> 35:05.860
Right, because it's still me saying it.

35:05.860 --> 35:12.620
Over years of speaking, all those slight variations dig a wide, recognizable trench.

35:13.500 --> 35:16.100
That is the word basin for your hello.

35:16.820 --> 35:21.180
And the architecture that manages all of these trenches is called TARTAN.

35:22.080 --> 35:22.600
Correct.

35:23.160 --> 35:27.840
TARTAN stands for Trajectory Aware Recursive Tiling with Annotated Noise.

35:28.000 --> 35:32.500
That is easily the most sci-fi acronym I have ever heard in a research paper.

35:32.500 --> 35:34.340
It sounds like it belongs on a starship.

35:34.660 --> 35:35.360
It really does.

35:35.840 --> 35:38.480
How does the TARTAN architecture actually operate?

35:38.700 --> 35:45.960
The key innovation of TARTAN lies in its salience marker enumeration, and specifically how it handles a marker called fracture.

35:46.380 --> 35:46.980
Fracture.

35:47.200 --> 35:47.980
Sounds intense.

35:48.460 --> 35:58.560
Usually when an audio system encounters silence, say, the speaker pauses to take a breath, or hesitates between words, the system just stops recording data.

35:58.700 --> 36:00.100
Because there's nothing to record.

36:00.100 --> 36:03.900
It treats silence as empty, null space.

36:05.300 --> 36:08.320
But TARTAN treats silence as a topological boundary.

36:08.840 --> 36:10.520
It drops a fracture marker.

36:10.980 --> 36:16.860
Silence as a topological boundary, meaning the pause is a physical wall in the architecture of the sentence.

36:17.260 --> 36:19.120
It is an active structural element.

36:19.380 --> 36:22.060
The lack of sound is not a lack of data.

36:22.540 --> 36:26.020
The tining and placement of the silence is the data.

36:26.020 --> 36:37.640
That immediately makes me think of the famous quote usually attributed to Mozart or sometimes Claude Debussy, where he says, the music is not in the notes, but in the silence between.

36:38.000 --> 36:41.240
Oh, that's beautiful and entirely accurate here.

36:41.280 --> 36:48.900
The notes just give context to the silence, the tension, the anticipation, the hesitation that all lives in the empty space.

36:48.900 --> 36:53.580
That is fundamentally true of human speech, and TARTAN maps it geometrically.

36:53.620 --> 36:54.880
What does that look on the screen?

36:55.600 --> 36:59.860
In standard text, a pause is just a standard spacebar gap.

36:59.860 --> 37:06.760
But in hyperbionic text, silence is rendered as highly specific proportional white space.

37:07.240 --> 37:08.900
Oh, proportional white space.

37:08.900 --> 37:13.980
The absence of a prosodic transformation on the page is the prosodic signal.

37:15.100 --> 37:24.400
If the speaker hesitates for a microsecond, the trajectory hits a topological gap, and the visual text incorporates that exact gap.

37:24.620 --> 37:27.960
So the spaces between words stretch out.

37:27.960 --> 37:47.480
Furthermore, the system is mathematically rigid about distinguishing between a very quiet, breathy whisper, which has low salience and renders as faded, transparent text, and absolute true silence, which generates a fracture marker and creates white space.

37:47.640 --> 37:52.300
Okay, I want to go back to the word basins for a second, because I see a massive flaw here.

37:52.400 --> 37:53.520
A flaw. Let's hear it.

37:53.520 --> 37:59.200
We said that my voice digs a specific trench, a basin, for the word hello.

37:59.520 --> 37:59.800
Right.

38:00.040 --> 38:04.840
But what happens when someone else says the word hello? We all speak at vastly different speeds.

38:05.040 --> 38:05.320
True.

38:05.500 --> 38:16.840
My quick northeast hello might take a fraction of a second. But if I talk to someone from the deep south, they might give me a long, drawn-out hello that takes two full seconds to complete.

38:16.960 --> 38:18.100
A totally different duration.

38:18.100 --> 38:22.300
The glowing dot is moving through the lattice much, much slower.

38:23.520 --> 38:30.600
How can the system possibly recognize both of those completely different timelines as the exact same word, basin?

38:30.600 --> 38:39.600
To solve that exact problem, the system utilizes a powerful algorithm called dynamic time warping, or DTW.

38:39.960 --> 38:46.900
Dynamic time warping. I am going to need an analogy for that. How does a piece of software stretch time?

38:47.460 --> 38:56.860
Let's build an analogy using a city grid. Imagine you have a map of a city block, represented as a grid or a matrix.

38:56.860 --> 38:58.860
Okay, I'm picturing a grid.

38:58.860 --> 39:07.860
On the x-axis, you plot the acoustic sequence of your fast hello. On the y-axis, you plot the acoustic sequence of the slow hello.

39:07.860 --> 39:08.860
Alright.

39:08.860 --> 39:16.860
The DTW algorithm places a point at the start of the 8 sound, and needs to find a path through this grid to the end of the O sound.

39:16.860 --> 39:19.860
Okay, so it's trying to map one sound onto the other.

39:19.860 --> 39:27.860
Exactly. The algorithm calculates the cost of moving through each square of the grid based on how similar the acoustic features are at that moment.

39:27.860 --> 39:29.860
How does it handle the slow part?

39:29.860 --> 39:38.860
Because the slow hello holds the L sound for a very long time, the algorithm doesn't just draw a straight diagonal line.

39:38.860 --> 39:46.860
It moves horizontally across the grid, matching your single fast L to many frames of the slow L before moving on.

39:46.860 --> 39:47.860
Oh, nice.

39:47.860 --> 39:53.860
It calculates the shortest, most efficient path through the matrix that aligns the sequence of the sounds.

39:53.860 --> 40:03.860
So it maps the topography. It doesn't care about the absolute ticking of the clock. It just says, okay, we had a rise in pitch, followed by a long plateau, followed by a drop.

40:03.860 --> 40:04.860
Exactly.

40:04.860 --> 40:14.860
Whether that sequence took half a second or three seconds, the topological sequence, the shape of the mountain range, is identical.

40:14.860 --> 40:21.860
You have grasped it perfectly. DTW stretches and compresses the timeline to align the trajectories.

40:21.860 --> 40:23.860
That's incredibly smart.

40:23.860 --> 40:32.860
It replaces the archaic method of speech recognition, which tries to chop sounds into fixed phonetic labels with a continuous geometric resonance.

40:32.860 --> 40:34.860
The geometric resonance.

40:34.860 --> 40:42.860
The system simply asks, regardless of speed, does the shape of this incoming sound wave resonate with the shape of the basin we have stored?

40:42.860 --> 40:53.860
That is incredibly elegant. So to recap where we are right now, we have an engine that mathematically extracts the emotional geometry of a human voice.

40:53.860 --> 40:54.860
Right.

40:54.860 --> 40:58.860
It handles varying speeds of speech through dynamic time warping.

40:58.860 --> 40:59.860
Yeah.

40:59.860 --> 41:11.860
It renders this geometry onto a screen using subtle typographic shifts, and it uses constraint energy equations to guarantee that the text doesn't become a nauseating blur.

41:11.860 --> 41:12.860
Exactly.

41:12.860 --> 41:20.860
This is a brilliant engineering feat, but what is the practical, real-world application of this? Why build it?

41:20.860 --> 41:27.860
Ah. This brings us to the pivot of the paper, what I consider the absolute climax of this research.

41:27.860 --> 41:30.860
We are talking about the deepfake detector.

41:30.860 --> 41:31.860
We are.

41:31.860 --> 41:36.860
And this entire application hinges on completely redefining how we view jitter.

41:36.860 --> 41:41.860
This is where the paper moves from communication theory into profound cybersecurity implications.

41:41.860 --> 41:43.860
Okay. Set the stage.

41:43.860 --> 41:50.860
As we mentioned earlier, in standard audio engineering, jitter is a deviation from perfect metronomic timing or pitch.

41:50.860 --> 41:53.860
Classical processing treats all jitter as noise.

41:53.860 --> 41:55.860
Right. It's an error.

41:55.860 --> 42:02.860
It is an error that needs to be normalized, smoothed out, or filtered away by auto-tune algorithms.

42:02.860 --> 42:03.860
Hmm.

42:03.860 --> 42:05.860
But Flyxion makes a radical argument.

42:05.860 --> 42:08.860
This approach is fundamentally flawed.

42:08.860 --> 42:09.860
Why?

42:09.860 --> 42:12.860
Structured deviation is not noise.

42:12.860 --> 42:15.860
It is the primary carrier of human intention.

42:15.860 --> 42:17.860
Structured deviation.

42:17.860 --> 42:22.860
Let me try to visualize why perfection is actually the problem here.

42:22.860 --> 42:23.860
Go for it.

42:23.860 --> 42:27.860
Imagine you tell a computer program to draw a circle.

42:27.860 --> 42:38.860
It calculates pi to a thousand decimal places, plots every pixel flawlessly, and prints a perfectly smooth, mathematically absolute circle.

42:38.860 --> 42:39.860
A perfect circle.

42:39.860 --> 42:42.860
Now, imagine a master Japanese calligrapher.

42:42.860 --> 42:50.860
They take a bamboo brush, dip it in ink, take a breath, and draw an ENSO circle in one fluid, sweeping motion.

42:50.860 --> 42:51.860
Beautiful.

42:51.860 --> 42:55.860
Now, if you run a geometry test on the calligrapher circle, it fails.

42:55.860 --> 42:57.860
It is full of errors.

42:57.860 --> 43:02.860
The brush bristles skipped on the paper, the pressure varied, the ink bled.

43:02.860 --> 43:04.860
The arc isn't perfectly symmetrical.

43:04.860 --> 43:06.860
It has massive amounts of jitter.

43:06.860 --> 43:08.860
But which circle has more meaning?

43:08.860 --> 43:09.860
Exactly.

43:09.860 --> 43:11.860
We look at the computer circle, and it is sterile.

43:11.860 --> 43:12.860
It's dead.

43:12.860 --> 43:16.860
We look at the calligrapher circle, and we see beauty.

43:16.860 --> 43:22.860
We see the breath, the physical tension of the hand, the intention of the artist.

43:22.860 --> 43:25.860
The imperfections are the art.

43:25.860 --> 43:29.860
That aesthetic reality translates directly into acoustic mathematics.

43:29.860 --> 43:31.860
How so?

43:31.860 --> 43:40.860
The paper formalizes this distinction by introducing a metric called expressive coherence, which is denoted by the Greek letter chi.

43:40.860 --> 43:41.860
Chi.

43:41.860 --> 43:42.860
Okay.

43:42.860 --> 43:53.860
Expressive coherence is an algorithmic measure that distinguishes between random, meaningless jitter, like the crackle of a bad microphone cable, and structured living jitter.

43:53.860 --> 43:54.860
Living jitter.

43:54.860 --> 43:55.860
Living jitter.

43:55.860 --> 43:56.860
Like the calligrapher's brush.

43:56.860 --> 43:57.860
Exactly.

43:57.860 --> 44:04.860
Like the micro fluctuations of a singer's vibrato, or the microscopic swing a jazz drummer uses that gives a beat its groove.

44:04.860 --> 44:13.860
So the software can mathematically distinguish between the flawless, dead perfection of a machine and the structured living imperfection of a human being.

44:13.860 --> 44:14.860
It absolutely can.

44:14.860 --> 44:19.860
Does that mean we could use this type of graphic system to catch an AI deepfake?

44:19.860 --> 44:24.860
Not only could we, but the paper proposes this as a primary application.

44:24.860 --> 44:29.860
It relies on a physiological principle called biological coupling.

44:29.860 --> 44:30.860
Biological coupling.

44:30.860 --> 44:32.860
Let's dig into the physical reality of that.

44:32.860 --> 44:37.860
Think about the biomechanics required to produce a single spoken word.

44:37.860 --> 44:41.860
Sound is not generated by a microchip in a vacuum.

44:41.860 --> 44:42.860
No.

44:42.860 --> 44:48.860
It is the output of a highly complex, interconnected, physical meat system.

44:48.860 --> 44:49.860
A meat system.

44:49.860 --> 44:50.860
A meat system.

44:50.860 --> 44:52.860
That's a gross but accurate way to put it.

44:52.860 --> 44:53.860
C-speak.

44:53.860 --> 44:57.860
Your lungs must compress to push air upward.

44:57.860 --> 44:59.860
Your diaphragm is flexing.

44:59.860 --> 45:04.860
The air passes through your trachea, forcing your vocal cords to physically vibrate.

45:04.860 --> 45:05.860
Right.

45:05.860 --> 45:11.860
That sound wave then bounces around the resonant cavities of your chest, your throat, and your skull.

45:11.860 --> 45:14.860
Your tongue, teeth, and lips shape the final wave.

45:14.860 --> 45:19.860
And all of this is being managed simultaneously by your neural motor control.

45:19.860 --> 45:25.860
It is an incredibly violent physical act involving dozens of muscles working in tandem.

45:25.860 --> 45:32.860
Because of that inescapable physical reality, the micro jitters in a human voice are never truly random.

45:32.860 --> 45:35.860
They are constrained and structured by your biology.

45:35.860 --> 45:36.860
Wait, really?

45:36.860 --> 45:37.860
Yes.

45:37.860 --> 45:39.860
The pulsing of your heartbeat.

45:39.860 --> 45:42.860
The phase of your respiratory cycle.

45:42.860 --> 45:46.860
The microscopic fatigue of the muscles in your throat.

45:46.860 --> 45:58.860
All of these biological rhythms impose a consistent, mathematically recognizable pattern on the audio wave across multiple timescales.

45:58.860 --> 45:59.860
That is wild.

45:59.860 --> 46:04.860
The jitter in your voice is mechanically coupled to the meat of your body.

46:04.860 --> 46:09.860
And an AI voice synthesizer running on a server farm doesn't have a diaphragm.

46:09.860 --> 46:10.860
It doesn't have a heartbeat.

46:10.860 --> 46:11.860
Exactly.

46:11.860 --> 46:17.860
Generative AI audio models are terrifyingly good at mimicking the macro statistics of a voice.

46:17.860 --> 46:19.860
They sound so real now.

46:19.860 --> 46:27.860
If they analyze enough audio of a politician, they can perfectly fake the average pitch, the spectral envelope, and the overall volume.

46:27.860 --> 46:29.860
They can fool your ear easily.

46:29.860 --> 46:30.860
Uh-huh.

46:30.860 --> 46:35.860
But they fail completely to fake the biological coupling of a physical body.

46:35.860 --> 46:42.860
When an AI generates micro fluctuations to sound more natural, it is just sampling numbers from a statistical distribution.

46:42.860 --> 46:45.860
It's just random number generation?

46:45.860 --> 46:48.860
It is not simulating the physical compression of lungs.

46:48.860 --> 46:53.860
So the AI matches the statistics, but it fundamentally fails the biology.

46:53.860 --> 46:58.860
The paper refers to this as decoupled synthetic jitter.

46:58.860 --> 47:11.860
And because the marine processor and the Tartan architecture explicitly calculate expressive coherence, looking specifically for that biological signature, it identifies the deep fake instantly.

47:11.860 --> 47:12.860
He just knows.

47:12.860 --> 47:19.860
The geometric basin of a synthesized voice lacks the topographical complexity of a breathing body.

47:19.860 --> 47:23.860
So how does that mathematically flag manifest on the screen?

47:23.860 --> 47:24.860
Visually, you mean?

47:24.860 --> 47:25.860
Yeah.

47:25.860 --> 47:36.860
If I am looking at a hyperbionic transcript, and one paragraph is a real human speaking, and the next paragraph is an AI deep fake trying to sound exactly like them, what is the visual difference?

47:36.860 --> 47:40.860
The paper details this exact comparison.

47:40.860 --> 47:47.860
Statistically, the human and the AI might have the exact same average pitch and amplitude.

47:47.860 --> 47:48.860
But visually?

47:48.860 --> 47:50.860
Visually, they diverge completely.

47:50.860 --> 48:01.860
Because the robotic voice lacks expressive coherence, the hyperbionic rendering would translate it as straight, linear, unnaturally uniform text.

48:01.860 --> 48:03.860
It would look flat and dead on the screen.

48:03.860 --> 48:12.860
The human voice, however, possessing high expressive coherence, would render as a dynamic, oscillating wave.

48:12.860 --> 48:21.860
The text would visibly pulse, the bass line shifting and the opacity breathing in rhythm with the biological machinery of the speaker.

48:21.860 --> 48:24.860
So I wouldn't need an audio lab to detect the deep fake.

48:24.860 --> 48:25.860
Not at all.

48:25.860 --> 48:30.860
Just literally just look at the text and see that a human body did not produce those words.

48:30.860 --> 48:35.860
We're talking about using typography as a biometric polygraph test.

48:35.860 --> 48:37.860
That gives me chills.

48:37.860 --> 48:43.860
The physical text on the screen becomes undeniable proof of the humanity of the speaker.

48:43.860 --> 48:47.860
That is a profound application of information theory.

48:47.860 --> 48:55.860
And this physical biological connection leads us directly into the final major concept explored in the paper.

48:55.860 --> 48:56.860
Okay, let's get into it.

48:56.860 --> 49:02.860
We have established that speaking has a physical geometry and that we can map that geometry onto a page.

49:02.860 --> 49:03.860
Right.

49:03.860 --> 49:06.860
But the paper takes it one step further.

49:06.860 --> 49:12.860
It argues that reading this hyperbionic text involves a physical geometry as well.

49:12.860 --> 49:15.860
It connects this to something called the ergodic writing process.

49:15.860 --> 49:17.860
Ergodic writing process.

49:17.860 --> 49:22.860
Ergodic in this context refers to navigating a space, right?

49:22.860 --> 49:26.860
Yes, the biomechanics of reading and writing.

49:26.860 --> 49:36.860
The paper describes a phenomenon that every single person listening to this experiences multiple times a day when using a smartphone or a keyboard.

49:36.860 --> 49:37.860
Which is?

49:37.860 --> 49:44.860
It is the spontaneous subconscious switching between two distinct modes of writing.

49:44.860 --> 49:47.860
Continuous flow and discrete construction.

49:47.860 --> 49:50.860
Continuous flow versus discrete construction.

49:50.860 --> 49:53.860
Let's map this to a real world behavior.

49:53.860 --> 50:00.860
Are we talking about the difference between using a swipe keyboard on my phone versus tapping out individual letters?

50:00.860 --> 50:02.860
That is the perfect example.

50:02.860 --> 50:08.860
Think about what your thumb is doing when you type a highly familiar everyday phrase like sounds good.

50:08.860 --> 50:09.860
Okay.

50:09.860 --> 50:13.860
If you use a swipe keyboard, you do not look at the individual letters.

50:13.860 --> 50:16.860
You don't think about S then O then U.

50:16.860 --> 50:22.860
You simply execute a single fluid motor gesture across the glass screen.

50:22.860 --> 50:23.860
Yeah.

50:23.860 --> 50:25.860
My thumb traces a continuous physical path.

50:25.860 --> 50:29.860
That sweeping path is a deeply stored motor basin in your brain.

50:29.860 --> 50:32.860
You have memorized the physical dance of the phrase.

50:32.860 --> 50:35.860
My thumb just knows the choreography.

50:35.860 --> 50:37.860
But what happens when you have to type something new?

50:37.860 --> 50:42.860
Like texting someone the last name of a brand new co-worker and name I've never typed before.

50:42.860 --> 50:43.860
Exactly.

50:43.860 --> 50:45.860
The choreography completely fails.

50:45.860 --> 50:47.860
My thumb completely stops dancing.

50:47.860 --> 50:54.860
I have to physically look at the keyboard, hunt for each specific letter, and peck them out one by one.

50:54.860 --> 50:58.860
I switch to discrete construction.

50:58.860 --> 50:59.860
Exactly.

50:59.860 --> 51:05.860
The paper theorizes that this instantaneous switching is governed by trajectory predictability.

51:05.860 --> 51:07.860
Trajectory predictability.

51:07.860 --> 51:16.860
When the physical trajectory of the word is known and deeply familiar to your motor cortex, you execute a continuous motor plan.

51:16.860 --> 51:18.860
You glide through the basin.

51:18.860 --> 51:20.860
Because I've done it a thousand times.

51:20.860 --> 51:26.860
When the word is unfamiliar, the continuous plan fails, and you are forced to discretize it.

51:26.860 --> 51:29.860
You build the word block by block.

51:29.860 --> 51:35.860
You traverse familiar spaces continuously, and you explore unknown spaces discreetly.

51:35.860 --> 51:39.860
That makes perfect intuitive sense for how we write with our hands.

51:39.860 --> 51:42.860
We can feel the difference in the tension in our thumbs.

51:42.860 --> 51:49.860
So the paper makes a highly specific, testable prediction regarding keyboard layouts to prove this point right.

51:49.860 --> 51:54.860
Oh yeah, it brings up the QWERTY layout versus the Dvorak layout.

51:54.860 --> 51:55.860
It does.

51:55.860 --> 52:01.860
It predicts the precise nature of the speed penalty when a typist switches layouts.

52:01.860 --> 52:03.860
Okay, let me logic this out.

52:03.860 --> 52:04.860
Walk us through it.

52:04.860 --> 52:05.860
Walk us through it.

52:05.860 --> 52:20.860
If you take a user who has typed on a standard QWERTY keyboard for 20 years, and you force them to type on a Dvorak keyboard, where the letters are arranged completely differently, obviously, their overall typing speed will plummet.

52:20.860 --> 52:21.860
Yes, that's a given.

52:21.860 --> 52:28.860
But the paper predicts that the speed penalty will not be uniform across their vocabulary.

52:28.860 --> 52:29.860
Exactly.

52:29.860 --> 52:42.860
The words that I type the most, the familiar words that I used a continuous sweeping gesture for on the gritty keyboard, those words will suffer a massive catastrophic speed penalty.

52:42.860 --> 52:43.860
Because?

52:43.860 --> 52:46.860
Because my brain didn't just memorize the spelling.

52:46.860 --> 52:49.860
My brain memorized the physical shape of the swipe.

52:49.860 --> 52:54.860
And on the Dvorak keyboard, that physical shape is now completely useless.

52:54.860 --> 52:56.860
It generates gibberish.

52:56.860 --> 52:57.860
Spot on.

52:57.860 --> 53:08.860
But the unfamiliar words, the ones I always had to hunt and peck letter by letter anyway, will transfer over much easier because my brain was already using discrete construction for them.

53:08.860 --> 53:11.860
That is exactly the prediction.

53:11.860 --> 53:18.860
It demonstrates that our brains do not merely store linguistic information as abstract spelling.

53:18.860 --> 53:24.860
We store the physical, spatial trajectory of how to biologically execute the word.

53:24.860 --> 53:25.860
Okay.

53:25.860 --> 53:32.860
I understand how the physical motion of writing is stored in our bodies, but how does this connect to the physical act of reading?

53:32.860 --> 53:34.860
This is the final leap.

53:34.860 --> 53:37.860
I am not swiping my thumb when I read an email.

53:37.860 --> 53:46.860
Are we actually suggesting that staring at hyperbionic text on a screen is going to trigger a physical motor reflex in the reader's body?

53:46.860 --> 53:48.860
We are suggesting exactly that.

53:48.860 --> 53:49.860
Really?

53:49.860 --> 53:58.860
To understand the mechanism behind this, the paper leans heavily on cognitive scientist Arnie Cox's theory of the mimetic proxy.

53:58.860 --> 54:03.860
And it brilliantly illustrates this using American Sign Language or ASL.

54:03.860 --> 54:06.860
ASL is such a fundamentally different way of communicating.

54:06.860 --> 54:09.860
How does its structure illuminate this theory?

54:09.860 --> 54:16.860
In a spoken language like English, if we want to describe urgency, we usually add a discrete lexical unit.

54:16.860 --> 54:17.860
We add a word.

54:17.860 --> 54:18.860
We say, he ran very fast.

54:18.860 --> 54:24.860
But in American Sign Language, you often do not add a separate sign for very.

54:24.860 --> 54:30.860
You encode the aspect of urgency directly into the physical motion of the sign itself.

54:30.860 --> 54:31.860
Oh, I see.

54:31.860 --> 54:37.860
A sign performed with increased velocity and sharp deceleration encodes urgency.

54:37.860 --> 54:44.860
A sign performed with an expanded spatial reach encodes massive scale.

54:44.860 --> 54:50.860
The semantic meaning is inextricably bound to the physical motion of the body performing it.

54:50.860 --> 54:53.860
The physical medium is literally the message.

54:53.860 --> 54:58.860
You cannot separate what is being said from how the body moves to say it.

54:58.860 --> 54:59.860
Exactly.

54:59.860 --> 55:09.860
Now, Arnie Cox's theory of embodied cognition, particularly regarding music, argues that this physical linkage exists even when we only hear a sound.

55:09.860 --> 55:10.860
Even when we just hear it.

55:10.860 --> 55:16.860
When you listen to an audio cue, your brain does not merely act as a passive receiver of data.

55:16.860 --> 55:25.860
To interpret the sound, your brain covertly neurologically simulates the physical gesture that would be required to produce that sound.

55:25.860 --> 55:34.860
Wait, so if I hear a loud, sharp, staccato snare drum hit, my brain is subtly simulating the physical motion of striking a surface with a stick.

55:34.860 --> 55:43.860
